<HEAD>Tower Backed Defense Buildup, Has Been Defense Consultant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has turned for his defense secretary to a former senator who strongly backed the military buildup of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years and worked as a consultant for major military contractors after leaving <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>, a 63-year-old Texan, retired from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 after 24 years including a stint as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. After leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, Tower went into business as a defense consultant. He also has served as an arms negotiator for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, and he headed the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s Iran-Contra investigative panel. He was widely mentioned as a candidate for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> job _ by most accounts the only one he really wanted _ under <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> never made the move. Tower comes to the job now at a time when the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> faces acute budget pressures because of the federal budget deficit and the array of costly new weapons systems developed as part of the military buildup. `` The bottom line is that we must provide at least as much, if not more, defense for less money,'' <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> said after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced his nomination Friday. The announcement followed a lengthy background check that brought a public airing of Tower's private life, including an acrimonious divorce, talk of drinking and womanizing, and questions about the propriety of naming someone to the job who had worked with so many defense companies. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> dismissed `` a lot of rumors that proved to be groundless'' and said, `` I am totally satisfied in that regard.'' The president-elect apparently decided that Tower's extensive financial ties to weapons companies that he will do business with as <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary was not a bar to service. Asked if Tower would stay out of <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> matters involving corporations for whom he has consulted, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` I expect so, but I do n't know. I expect he would, just like anybody coming in. ... I think we'll bend over backward in that regard.'' According to public records and associates, Tower's consulting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> has been on annual retainer with the following defense contractors: <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Marietta </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Textron </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and British Aerospace. In addition, Tower's firm received about $ 100,000 a year under a contract for consulting services to <ORGANIZATION> Hicks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> McLean </LOCATION>, Va.-based aerospace consulting firm headed by <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, a former undersecretary of defense. Through <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>' firm, Tower indirectly provided advice to still more defense contractors. Tower's firm received $ 96,000 a year from <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>. Although other fees were not revealed, an associate, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Billmire </PERSON>, acknowledged some were in the range of $ 100,000 a year. `` There are some retainers in the neighborhood of that figure, and others that are substantially less,'' <PERSON> Billmire </PERSON> said. Tower also received income from speeches _ about $ 15,000 each for the 30 or so a year he gives, according to his agent <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON>. He has a second consulting firm, Dallas-based Tower, <ORGANIZATION> Eggers </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, which is described as providing financial services and advice. Tower was a former board member of a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> bank, <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. With his <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> firm, <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> was part of a group that unsuccessfully bid to buy the financially troubled bank before it was taken over by North Carolina-based <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Billmire </PERSON> described Tower's work for the defense contractors as providing advice on the direction of future defense projects and advice and information on government budget processes, including the transfer of money among projects <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said he signed a contract for Tower's services in order to gain the benefit of his advice and opinions about what <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was likely to do on defense issues. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, Tower was a supporter of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Strategic Defense Initiative and the MX missile. But he was said to be angered by the administration's failure to agree on a missile deployment plan and he moved to block development until an acceptable plan was found. Tower left the arms negotiating post after 14 months, and in late 1986 <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> named him to head his Iran-Contra investigative panel. Its report laid part of the blame for affair on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s management style _ but had little to say about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s involvement. In naming Tower, <PERSON> Bush </PERS