 Here is a look at <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>, President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choice for defense secretary. AGE: 63. EDUCATION: Tower received his undergraduate degree from <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and did graduate work at <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> and Political Science. BACKGROUND: The son of a Methodist minister, Tower was in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> during World War II. After the war, he worked as a radio announcer and insurance salesman before teaching political science at <ORGANIZATION> Midwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. CONGRESSIONAL SERVICE: He was narrowly elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1961, winning a special election to fill the seat vacated by <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> when <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> became vice president. On the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, he made a name for himself as an expert on the details of weapons systems and defense policy. After Republicans gained control of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1980, Tower became committee chairman. He became the chief legislative champion of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s defense spending build-up and a deeply conservative critic of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. CONSULTANT: He retired in 1984 to become a high-priced <LOCATION> Washington </LOC