<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> filed a lawsuit against the city Friday, accusing housing officials of `` systematic warrantless searches'' of tenants and their visitors in an effort to crack down on drug selling. <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> officials later agreed to relax some of the security rules, but the lawsuit was not withdrawn from <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, said agency spokeswoman <PERSON> Katie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>. The lawsuit stems from a security crackdown by the housing agency, which is trying to evict squatters and violent gang members who use the projects as havens for drug deals. The lawsuit seeks to stop searches of tenants and their apartments and to establish `` reasonable regulations'' on visits by family members and other guests. Under the existing regulations, `` all guests of residents in the building have to sign in with the guard at the front door and show a piece of valid identification,'' Ms. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. `` The policy has been that guests are asked to leave the building at midnight and are not allowed in until 9 a.m.,'' she said. No overnight guests are allowed unless the tenant has received prior approval. The lawsuit says housing officials and police `` have indiscriminately detained and searched tenants' persons and homes, going through drawers closets, personal effects'' and other items. `` These searches have been carried out without the consent of the tenants and any prior notice. If tenants object, they have been threatened with arrest,'' the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The lawsuit cites the case of a tenant who was forced to find another babysitter for her sister's children after housing officials ordered the children out of her apartment at midnight. Under the new rules, `` The guest upon entry, will identify him or herself to CHA personnel,'' but will not need a piece of identification, although the tenant must confirm that the person is a guest, Ms. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. Overnight visitors would be issued guest cards, and residents could have long-term guests for a period of up to two weeks. Ms. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> planned to present the proposals to the plaintiffs, and planned further discussions with the city. `` Our intent in all our security procedures is to provide for the safety and welfare of our residents and that will continue to be our objective,'' she said. The defendants are the housing agency, the city and police Superintendent <PERSON> LeRoy </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>.
