<HEAD>Panels Urges Restrictions On Alcohol Advertising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal panel is calling for restrictions on alcohol advertising and higher state and federal excise taxes in an effort to reduce drunken driving by discouraging alcohol consumption. Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> accepted an inch-thick packet of recommendations Friday at the close of a three-day workshop he convened, and he vowed to use his high public profile to publicize the report. While stopping short of urging an outright ban of beer, wine and liquor advertising, the panel said such ads should not be allowed on college campuses `` since a high proportion of audience reached is under the legal drinking age.'' <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> told the workshop participants that his office had little money or power to implement policy, but promised to provide start-up funds for a non-profit, private corporation to serve as a clearinghouse for groups seeking ammunition to use in the war on drunken driving. <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> said that, for his part, he intends to be an aggressive but not shrill soldier. `` I intend to ignore those who would lynch or execute a first offender in drunk driving just as I will ignore those who would say it has not yet been proven that alcohol is responsible for impaired driving,'' <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> told the workshop. `` I intend to pursue whatever leadership role I may have between these two extremes as I have with other issues and to transmit to that leadership whatever energy, enthusiasm and credibility I have in this war against impaired driving.'' The panel's other recommendations called for: _ Elimination of alcohol advertising and promotion and sponsorship of public events where the majority of the audience is under the legal drinking age _ Elimination of advertising that portrays activities that are combined with alcohol use _ Banning of sponsorship of athletic events by the alcohol beverage industry _ Blocking the use of celebrities who have a strong appeal to young people in alcohol advertising and promotion _ Requiring that the warning labels <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> recently voted to require on alcoholic containers also be required to appear clearly and conspicuously in all alcohol ads No specific monetary figures were contained in the section on taxes, but the panelist said excise tax rates at both the federal and state level should be equalized among beer, wine and liquor and indexed to rise automatically with inflation. The advertising section was most controversial, largely because the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> and the advertising industry had declined to participate in the workshop, claiming it was stacked against advertisers' interests. `` In fact, the research the ad industry provided the panel demonstrates that there is no existing evidence that links advertising and alcohol abuse,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> in a statement Friday. NAB President <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> last month: `` At best, this workshop is designed to politicize the emotional tragedy of drunk driving. At worst, it is a total abuse of the policy-setting process.'' <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>, who had not responded publicly to that charge, lashed back at the end of his remarks Friday. `` I wanted everyone to hear the <ORGANIZATION> NAB </ORGANIZATION>'s point of view not only because broadcasters are very influential, but because they also have so much at stake in this issue,'' he said. `` Hence, they certainly have the right to be here.'' <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> said he felt the criticism of the workshop was unfair and said he was `` taken aback'' by what he called <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON>' `` unfortunate choice of words.''
