<HEAD>President Says America No Longer The Dominant Global Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in the last major foreign policy speech of his presidency that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` no longer enjoys preponderant power'' in the world. As a result, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, his Oval Office successors and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must not treat each other as `` adversaries'' but must work more cooperatively if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to be successful in pursuing its interests in the global arena. `` It is precisely where <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president have worked together, as in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, or resolved differences, as in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> and many aspects of U.S.-Soviet relations, precisely there, -LRB- where -RRB- our policies have succeeded, and we see progress,'' the president on Friday told students and faculty at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION>, on the campus founded by <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>. `` But where <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president have engaged each other as adversaries _ as over <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policies have faltered and our common purposes have not been achieved,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he thought that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in recent years had taken on too great a role in making foreign policy. Instead of linking his own support for the Contra rebels to the difficulties in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> blamed <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' `` on-again, off-again indecisiveness on resisting Sandinista tyranny and aggression'' in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for leaving the area `` a region of continuing danger.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> complained about the War Powers Resolution, which gives <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> a veto power over the commitment of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops abroad after a 60-day period. He lamented attempts by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to `` manage complex issues of foreign policy by the blunt instrument of legislation, such as unduly restrictive intelligence oversight, limits on arms transfers and earmarking of 95 percent of our foreign assistance, denying a president the ability to respond flexibly to rapidly changing conditions.'' In his speech, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also lauded Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, saying `` let us credit him'' for his reforms. But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> added that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> must remain skeptical about the U.S.-Soviet relationship because `` serious problems, fundamental differences remain.'' `` Yes, we welcome Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s recent announcement of a troop reduction,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` but let us remember that the Soviet preponderance in military power in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> remains _ an asymmetry that offends our Jeffersonian senses _ and endangers our future.'' `` So we must keep our heads, and this means keeping our skepticism,'' he said. He credited <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> with taking `` some daring steps'' to bring about reforms that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said would have been unthinkable under former Soviet leaders <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. The president said the superpowers are `` coming closer'' to agreement on a <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ