<HEAD>Cost of New Bombers Put At More Than Half-Billion Dollars Apiece</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS first two grafs; picks up 3rd graf bgng: ``Aldridge
told...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The $ 516 million-per-plane pricetag for the B-2 stealth bomber makes it the most expensive aircraft ever built, but <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> says whatever the radar-evading plane costs, it's worth it. The stealth bomber, which resembles a huge, tailless manta ray, is expected to make its first flight early next year but will not be ready for wartime use until 1992 at the earliest, <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> said Friday. <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> told a news conference the design, development and construction of 132 planes was expected to cost $ 68.1 billion by the time production ends in mid-1995. Expressed in terms of the original estimate, the price tag has grown from $ 36.6 billion to $ 42.5 billion in fiscal 1981 dollars _ an increase of about 16 percent, <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> said. Those figures do not reflect cost increases caused by inflation since 1981 or that projected in future years. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must authorize and appropriate money for production, and the figures assume it will do so at the pace the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> proposes. <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> said a stretchout of production would boost the per-plane cost by 20 percent or more. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> gave the public its first glimpse of the aircraft at a ceremony in <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, last month. About one-third of the total cost of the long-range bomber is being spent on research and development. The actual production cost amounts to $ 305 million per plane, <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> said. `` Whatever it costs, it's worth it,'' <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> said. `` How much is deterrence worth? `` This thing is a significant contributor to the strategic deterrence of our country. The Soviets know it. They know the capabilities this aircraft can provide.'' <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON>, reviewing the results of a long-running internal review of the B-2, said the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> had decided to slow production of the bomber during the early years of the program and to accelerate production at the end. He refused to offer specific numbers, but he said the acceleration at the end of the program would be such that production of all 132 of the planes would be completed a year early, in mid-1995. The latest cost projection includes estimated savings of about $ 3 billion, the secretary continued, thanks to the changes in production and a decision to purchase more than 100 of the planes under a single, multiyear contract. Few of the planes will be built while the bomber is undergoing flight testing in the early years, <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> explained. Once the flight testing is completed and the design frozen, a multiyear contract can be negotiated to achieve the most economical rate of production, he added. <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> said a large portion of the cost increase _ about $ 1 billion in fiscal 1981 dollars _ `` results from a major redesign effort in 1983.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> secretary said the redesign was ordered because the stealth bomber originally was meant only to fly at high altitude. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> decided in 1983 that the plane should be able to fly at low altitude as well and that forced a redesign of its flying wing shape, he said. The B-2 gets its stealth name from the claim that it will be extremely difficult to detect by enemy radar due to the extensive use of exotic composite materials, its lack of sharp surface angles, and a cross-section that offers a very small profile to radar. It is built mainly by <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. At $ 516 million per copy, the B-2 would eclipse the new B-1B bomber, which cost about $ 280 million per copy, as the most expensive plane in the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> inventory The newest model of the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial aircraft, the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747, sells for roughly $ 125 million. <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON>, appearing before <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> reporters on his last day in office before joining the <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said the B-2 would fly for the first time `` as soon as it's ready,'' probably early next year. He said the first operational B-2 would be delivered to <ORGANIZATION> Whiteman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, in mid-1991 and that the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> probably will select three additional bases to house them. It probably will be at least 1992 before the plane is certified for `` initial operational capability,'' meaning it could fly in a war, <PERSON> Aldridge </PERSON> said.
