lantation mentality,'' the cardinal said. `` They do n't want this white pastor saying, ` Now you leave my black people alone, I'll take care of their needs.' `` We have the anomaly today of parishes which are predominantly black with a white pastor and a totally white staff. Why should n't these black people have the leadership in that parish Why should we be importing people from the suburbs, white people, to come in here and continue to run these parishes?'' Surveys found that 95 percent of the city's churches had strong black membership, but the operational structure was white, Auxiliary Bishop <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON> said Friday. `` We're not denying the value of what any white priest, sisters or brothers have done in the city. But sometime we have to stop and see what's best for the church and say, hey, it's time for black Catholic leaders to be seen and heard,'' <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON> said. But the Rev. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, pastor of <ORGANIZATION> Sacred </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pastoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, a group fighting the plan, said the assessment was distorted. `` We run our own parish here,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a white pastor, whose church staff members are mostly black residents of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. `` I think -LRB- <PERSON> Szoka </PERSON> -RRB- wants to do the right thing but he's being fed some very bad information and really is speaking with no experience on these things.'' <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON>, who has spent five years overseeing the study of urban churches, said he will deliver recommendations from appeal hearings on the closings to <PERSON> Szoka </PERSON> on Monday. The cardinal is expected to make a final decision during the first week in January. The archdiocese also released a letter of resignation Friday from a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Implementation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, one of two panels formed to help <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON> judge the viability of urban churches. Sister <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said in the letter that she believes the board will recommend closing churches that proved they were healthy in appeal hearings. `` Many parishes slated to close have in fact demonstrated viability in ways that could be models for other parishes,'' she said. Under the plan, 42 churches in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and one in nearby <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION> would close or merge with other parishes. Archdiocese officials held a series of hearings for parishes wishing to appeal the closings.
