<HEAD>Governors, Energy Department Lay Groundwork For Solving Nuclear
Waste Impasse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Energy Department should be able to meet conditions set by three governors for resolving a deadlock over the storage of radioactive waste from nuclear weapons plants, a department official said. The governors of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> emerged from a private meeting Friday with pledges of cooperation from Deputy Energy Secretary <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON>. `` I think we've laid a solid groundwork for progress. We've put a process in place. ... I believe it will bear fruit,'' <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON> said. But the governors said they would continue to pressure the government to make sure the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> honors its promise to hasten the opening of the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a prototype storage facility under construction near <LOCATION> Carlsbad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> `` We stand here today to say there is no way we can guarantee anything. There are uncertainties in the world, but I think we can bridge that,'' said <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> following the three-hour meeting. The officials announced progress toward resolving the most immediate problem, triggered when <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> closed his state's borders to waste shipments in October to try to force the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> into action. <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> said he would reconsider his decision if the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> speeded up the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> plant's opening. His decision is expected next month. <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> said he decided to reconsider after being told in a classified briefing that his ban on waste shipments into <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> could harm national security by forcing closure of the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant near <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. Since <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON>' order, the material has been piling up at Rocky Flats, which manufactures plutonium triggers for nuclear warheads. <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> has said he would close the plant when its temporary storage capacity is filled. That should occur between March and May. After the meeting, however, <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said he does n't anticipate closing the facility, although `` I can not work with additional storage in a metropolitan area of 1.5 million people.'' Waste is being stored temporarily at the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> until the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> plant opens, which <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON> said probably wo n't be until November or December 1989. The plant, originally scheduled to open last fall, will store wastes, including equipment and clothing that has been contaminated during the weapons-making process, in salt deposits more than 2,000 feet underground. <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> said that before he allows shipments to the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> plant to resume, the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> must also keep its pledge to introduce legislation and begin administrative procedures for a land swap with the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that must be completed before the pilot plant can open. The department also must prepare plans to remove the more than 4 million cubic feet of radioactive waste already stored in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. `` I said I would n't accept that old statement of ` trust me.' I said, ` show me,''' said <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON>. `` I said, ` If you're sincere, come back and prove it to me in January and we'll reconsider.''' <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON> said the department would appoint a task force to look for other temporary waste storage sites in case <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> refuses to lift his ban. But he expressed confidence that the necessary conditions could be met to continue operations at Rocky Flats and move forward with the opening of the pilot plant. One of the biggest stumbling blocks has been <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' failure to pass a bill to transfer several thousand acres of land around the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> plant from <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> control to the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The opening also has been delayed because of lapses in engineering assessments and questions about water leakage at the site. <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON> said the department will have a bill introduced when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> convenes in January. The department also will start administrative procedures for the exchange should <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> move too slowly, he said. `` Clearly, I think the DOE is trying to turn up the heat,'' <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Garrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Carruthers </PERSON> said at a news conference in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, upon his return from <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>.
