<SECOND>PM-Quake-Homeless, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0421,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anxious Armenian Villagers Await Rebuilding Of Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 16 grafs to UPDATE with rescue of 21 people, search to
continue for survivors. Picks up graf 17 pvs, `George Reid ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUSAKHPYUR, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The glow from an oil lamp illuminated the faces of the Armenian villagers who came in from the snow to visit the mayor in the plastic hut he and his family have lived in since the Dec. 7 earthquake. The mayor, <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Megerditchyan </PERSON>, who was pinned under a block of stone for several hours until his son rescued him, reassured the men of the village that their mountainside homes would be rebuilt within two years. `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he will do something, and he will,'' <PERSON> Megerditchyan </PERSON> said, referring to Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who toured the disaster area last week. In the meantime, authorities are faced with finding winter shelter for the estimated 500,000 survivors of one of the century's worst quakes The one-room corrugated shack, thrown up immediately after the earthquake with supplies from the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, is cool already, and will offer scant protection when temperatures drop further this winter. Throughout the region, Armenians are preparing to endure the approaching Soviet winter and recover from the shock of an earthquake that killed at least 55,000 people. In <LOCATION> Lusakhpyur </LOCATION>, about 600 of the 1,000 residents already have left seeking warmth in the homes of friends and relatives who survived the quake. Seventy villagers were killed, including 50 children crushed in a grade school corridor as they ran from collapsing classrooms. Ice-covered mountain roads connecting northwestern Armenian villages were bumper to bumper Thursday with cars, buses and trucks, listing under the weight of refugees and their few belongings. Soviet military trucks with supplies of bread, milk, meat, heavy coats and boots struggled through the traffic to deliver supplies to the needy. People generally did not appear hungry or in need of warm clothes, although some complained the emergency rations were n't being distributed fairly `` They select those they want to give to, and there is a hierarchy,'' said Asat Petzosyan of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, a city of about 25,000 almost wiped out by the quake. Officials say about 15,000 died in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>. `` I need somewhere to sleep,'' <PERSON> Petzosyan </PERSON> said, rubbing hands scarred from digging through the rubble searching for family and friends. `` All I have been given is this coat.'' <PERSON> Petzosyan </PERSON> and his neighbors have gathered pieces of broken furniture and torn mattresses to create living rooms without walls around outdoor bonfires, their only protection against the icy wind. Down the street, an elderly man stood motionless, surrounded by the roar of bulldozers, staring into a heap of rubble two-stories high. Tears ran down his unshaven cheeks. `` My granddaughter is in there,'' he said faintly. `` She is four. I'm waiting for her.'' But a happy ending is unlikely. Soviet authorities, fearing the spread of disease from decaying bodies, began razing <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION> on Friday. Later, workers rescued 21 people from the ruins in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, prompting authorities to extend their search for possible survivors. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Societies </ORGANIZATION>, said the greatest challenge now is providing shelter for those who remain. `` It is a terrible dilemma of conflicting needs _ the need for sanitation and the feelings of relatives,'' he said. `` Officials say they will evacuate 70,000 people, but that leaves 430,000 without homes,'' <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> said. `` Where do you put 430,000 people for the winter?'' The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> is bringing in 5,000 winter tents like those already delivered by the Norwegian army. And Soviet authorities are hoping to bring in by rail thousands of yurts, versions of the circular tents used for centuries on the frigid steppes of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Soviet soldiers are working beside civilian crews to quickly repair the rail lines just outside <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>. Soviet officials also hope to bring in thousands of mobile homes for the local men who will be rebuilding their town. <PERSON> Azen </PERSON> <PERSON> Akopyan </PERSON>, a worker at an elevator factory, will stay in the mobile home camp near <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>. His wife, <PERSON> Nina </PERSON>, will join her children next week at a temporary shelter set up by his trade union to house survivors. `` I do n't want to leave until <PERSON> Azen </PERSON> is in a warm place, but I wish they would hurry,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Akopyan </PERSON>, one of the few women in town who did not lose a member of her immediate family. `` When they rebuild <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, I guess I'll be back. But really, after all this, I am so afraid of the mountains.''
