<HEAD>Lear Jet Overshoots Destination, Crashes In Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Lear Jet flying from <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> mysteriously overflew its destination and crashed in rugged mountains of northern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> with two people aboard, officials said. Police spokesman <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Torreon </LOCATION> said the search for the plane was called off Friday because of darkness and rough terrain and would resume today, with the help of a farmer who reported seeing the downed plane and two bodies. The jet, which left <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, at about 5 a.m. Friday, crashed two or three hours later in a mountainous region 100 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The plane had a flight plan for <LOCATION> Addison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> suburb north of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Telkins </PERSON>, embassy press attache. An F-16 and another plane tried to intercept and contact the jet's pilot after the plane overshot its destination, but the pilot did not respond, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Araceli </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, a police spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Monclova </LOCATION>, 120 miles outside <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>, said authorities reported a small plane was seen early Friday and appeared in trouble, possibly low on fuel. `` Then they lost contact,'' Ms. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said by telephone. `` It appears to be a foreign plane.'' Ms. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said authorities immediately dispatched police units and a helicopter to search the area. The co-pilot was <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>, 25, of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, according to the craft's owner, <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Crownrich </PERSON>. The name of the pilot was not immediately known. <PERSON> Crownrich </PERSON>, who owns <ORGANIZATION> Crownrich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, said the jet was used for his business most of the time but was on a charter run at the time of the crash. Ms. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> and a pilot routinely flew to <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> to pick up <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> packages for delivery, he said. But <PERSON> Crownrich </PERSON> said the regular pilot was not aboard the latest flight. `` It came as a bolt of lighting to me,'' said <PERSON> Crownrich </PERSON>. `` I flew the plane yesterday to <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and it was just purring like a kitten'' at up to 45,000 feet, which is its normal flying altitude. He said something could have happened to the plane's occupants or the craft could have been sabotaged. `` It is pretty obvious that the plane was performing well and was bound to be on auto pilot, and it flew that course on until fuel starvation,'' he said. `` But why the pilot and co-pilot were not able to talk to the flight service is beyond me.''
