<HEAD>Jet Crash Lands in Bay Near Alameda Naval Air Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALAMEDA NAVAL AIR STATION, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> F-14 fighter jet struck another jet while attempting to land and crashed into nearby waters, but both crewmen aboard escaped uninjured, authorities said. The fighter crashed shortly before 7 p.m. Friday on approach to a runway at the air station, which occupies the northern end of an island 5 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. `` The whole plane was shattered into pieces of debris,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Coxswain <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON>, who was in charge of one of the rescue boats. The pilot and radar officer, who ejected from the aircraft, were pulled from the <ORGANIZATION> Alameda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estuary </ORGANIZATION>, one by a passing tugboat. The other was found about 150 yards from shore by the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> rescue boat. The crewmen, who were not identified, were taken to a naval hospital by ambulance, <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. He added both were in `` very good condition'' and were being observed for possible effects of shock. The aircraft was one of three F-14s in <LOCATION> Alameda </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Miramar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. The others had landed and the third was about to touch down when it clipped a wing of one of the F-14s already on the runway, said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Valente </PERSON>. The plane then veered off and crashed, sinking in about 12 feet of water, <PERSON> Valente </PERSON> said. In 1972, the $ 30 million F-14 Tomcat became the standard fleet flighter aboard aircraft carriers. It was popularized in the movie `` Top Gun'' starring <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruise </PERSON>. The plane's wings can extend to 64 feet for takeoff and landing and can be swept back to 33 feet to reduce air drag at high speeds.
