<HEAD>Service Calls at Tough Atlanta Housing Projected Resumed by Phone
Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> has reversed a decision to limit installations and repairs at four crime-riddled public housing projects, one of which is so violent that letter carriers get police escorts. The phone company had scaled back service in <LOCATION> Bankhead </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Courts </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Englewood </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardens </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Jonesboro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> apartments after a female technician was harassed at <LOCATION> Gilbert </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gardens </LOCATION> by six men who accused her of being a police officer. One man drew a gun while the others rifled her van. The woman was released when the resident whose phone she had repaired came outside and vouched for her, phone company spokesman <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendig </PERSON> said. The company had restricted service calls to Monday mornings, except for emergencies, and only allowed workers to enter the projects in groups. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> officials announced Friday that they were changing that policy and said they had scheduled a meeting Monday with Police Chief <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Redding </PERSON> to discuss security precautions. The <ORGANIZATION> Bankhead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courts </ORGANIZATION> housing project has a reputation for danger. Crime statistics on the project itself were unavailable, but the Zone 1 police precinct, which covers the 25 square miles encompassing the project, reported 41 homicides, 122 rapes and 609 robberies in 1987, said police spokeswoman <PERSON> Myrna </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON>. In October 1988, the zone reported six homicides, 16 rapes and 145 robberies, she said. Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> had condemned the phone service cutback, and <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoke </PERSON> said that the authority was `` outraged'' by it. Postal officials suspended service in the project for one day, after shots were fired near a letter carrier Dec. 10. City officials criticized the move, and service to the 500-unit complex resumed Wednesday under police escort. <PERSON> Kendig </PERSON> said the initial decision to restrict service calls resulted because `` we've had folks flash guns and pull knives on our installers, and threaten to use explosives on our vans.'' The service restrictions were the latest events in the Bankhead Courts crime drama, which police officials say has been violent and drug-ridden for most of its 19 years. Four police officers were injured there while making arrests in a Nov. 5 drug sweep that led to the arrest of 12 residents. A Nov. 10 raid, by 37 officers, led to 27 arrests _ nine on drug charges and 18 for traffic violations and other charges. A 24-year-old woman, who journeyed into the complex with friends, was killed Nov. 3 when a drug dealer, fearing undercover police officers, opened fire on her car as it approached with its headlights off.
