<HEAD>Palme's Widow Agrees to Identification Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The widow of Prime Minister <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Palme </PERSON> has agreed to try to identify a 41-year-old Swede being held in the investigation of her husband's assassination, a newspaper reported today. <PERSON> Christer </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>, who was arrested Wednesday, pleaded innocent Friday in a preliminary hearing, but a judge ruled there were reasonable grounds to suspect he killed <LOCATION> Palme </LOCATION> and ordered him held for further investigation. Palme, the dominant figure in Swedish politics for more than a decade, was killed Feb. 28, 1986 while walking home unguarded from a downtown movie theater with his wife <PERSON> Lisbet </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Palme </PERSON> was grazed by a bullet in the shooting, which took place at close range. The Expressen newspaper said Mrs. <PERSON> Palme </PERSON> was willing to try to identify the suspect but that it remained unclear whether she would be summoned to do so. `` We would like to spare her as long as possible,'' the newspaper quoted a source close to the investigation as saying. `` If we can do without her testimony we will try to do that.'' In another development, prosecutor <PERSON> Jorgen </PERSON> <PERSON> Almblad </PERSON> complained about the publication of <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>'s picture in foreign newspapers, saying that would complicate the case. `` If a witness says he has seen the photograph of a suspect in the paper, the value of the evidence will be rather low at a confrontation,'' <PERSON> Almblad </PERSON> said on Swedish Radio. Several witnesses have identified <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> as the man seen standing outside the movie theater before the Palmes emerged, press reports said Saturday. But no evidence has emerged that he was the gunman. The killer followed the couple down the street for several blocks before the shooting, then escaped down a dark alley. <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s press and libel regulations prohibit publication in this country of the names and pictures of suspects in criminal cases, in some instances even after a person has been convicted. However, personal information about Swedes is easily available from various national offices. Since his arrest, <PERSON> Petterson </PERSON>'s name has been a matter of public record, and anyone can obtain a picture of him for a 50-cent fee at the central passport office. Public records show <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> has a history of psychiatric treatment, drug and alcohol abuse and a long criminal record, including a conviction for manslaughter. Norwegian, Danish and English papers published the name and photograph of <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>, and foreign papers available in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION> were sold out at some news stands. Many papers hailed the arrest and Friday's arraignment as a major breakthrough in a case that has been a national frustration for nearly three years. Government commissions accused police of bungling in the crucial first days of the manhunt. The chief investigator has been replaced twice, and a private investigation led to the resignation of Justice Minister <PERSON> Anna-Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Leijon </PERSON> in June. But prosecutors have put forward no motive, and the murder weapon was not found. `` After nearly three years of uncertainty, the Palme murder is now on the way to a solution,'' anchor man <PERSON> Jarl </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfredius </PERSON> said on Friday's nightly news.
