<HEAD>Gandhi In China: First Visit Of Indian Leader In 34 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> comes to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Monday for the first visit by an Indian prime minister since his grandfather, <PERSON> Jawalharlal </PERSON> <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, made the trip 34 years ago. For <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s nation and his political future, the stakes appear high. For <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, little seemingly can go wrong. During a week long on symbolism but short on substance, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> will be feted in the capital, tour the ancient city of <LOCATION> Xian </LOCATION> and visit <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. The visit, <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> recently said, will be `` very important ... for this globe, for <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and for both of us.'' The two nations _ the world's most populous _ will probably sign agreements on civil aviation, border trade and science and technology, Indian and Western diplomats said, speaking on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> also may agree to establish consular offices. But no substantial progress is expected on the critical issue of their 2,400-mile border, over which the two countries fought a brief war in 1962. The two countries began border talks in 1981 but have made little progress. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> claims 36,000 square miles of Indian territory. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> rejects the claim and demands that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> return the 15,200 square miles it took in the 1962 war. Since then, relations have improved, but only slightly. The border remains heavily guarded on both sides and bilateral trade, which resumed in 1977 but amounted to only $ 150 million last year, is limited. Both <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> say <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s visit is intended to create an atmosphere for greater communication and not to resolve the border question. But Western diplomats said pressures on <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> could make him more willing to compromise than his Chinese counterparts. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is moving quickly to improve relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> after nearly three decades of hostility. A summit between Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> may be held next year. Better Chinese-Soviet relations will eliminate <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s need to cultivate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dehli </LOCATION> as a foil against <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. And by removing tensions along its northern border, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will be under less pressure to accomodate <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> on its southern flank. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> continues its close relationship with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s traditional enemy <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s new prime minister, <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, is expected to visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in January on her first official trip abroad. `` For <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, the whole visit has an air of him running along so he does n't get left out in the cold,'' said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> who recently returned from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. `` For the Chinese, the visit ca n't possibly go wrong.'' A society that speaks with one voice when it comes to foreign affairs, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has watched with apparent enjoyment as the Indian press has pressured <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> to make progress on the border issue, Western diplomats said. `` The prime minister has decided to stick yet another label to his travel bags,'' wrote the normally pro-government <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> in an editorial Wednesday. `` The more important question, however, is, what is the prime minister going to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for?'' <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> also faces an election next year in which victory is far from certain. Diplomats say he must convince his public that simply establishing goodwill with the Chinese _ and not achieving a dramatic breakthrough _ is a worthy goal. `` If he feels that he is failing at that, he might be persuaded to do something rash,'' the Western diplomat said. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> could use the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, the exiled <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> leader who has taken refuge in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> since 1959, to embarrass the Chinese. The Tibetan refugees' parliament-in-exile on Friday called on <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> to raise the issue of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> with Chinese leaders. But <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s hand is weakened by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s apparent willingness to crush dissent in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, regardless of international opinion. On Dec. 10, police shot and killed at least one monk in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, during an anti-Chinese demonstration. In addition, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> also has backed <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s claims to the region. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> was one of the first non-socialist countries to recognize <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the early 1950s. Relations soured in the early 1960s over the border question and political disagreements. Relations improved slightly in the late 1970s. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> invited an Indian leader to visit as early as 1979, but <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> agreed to come only in November of last year. Western diplomats say the timing of the acceptance was significant because it came well after Sino-Soviet relations had begun to improve.
