<HEAD>Ireland's State-Run Lottery to Fund AIDS Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s state-run lottery says it will supply free syringes, needles and contraceptives to drug addicts to help cut down their risk of contracting AIDS. The state-funded <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> agreed to distribute the items from two of its <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> centers because of a high incidence of needle sharing among drug addicts in the capital. The decisions were made Friday. Three years ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> approved a bill to legalize over-the-counter sales of contraceptives to anyone over 18 without a doctor's prescription. It was the first time in the state's history that a government had won a battle with the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes the use of contraceptives. About 97 percent of the population is <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. Lottery proceeds are used to finance projects in health, sports, the arts and the Irish language.
