<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> has stopped its longtime jamming of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-owned </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> broadcasting network, the government announced today. <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavel </PERSON>, a government spokesman, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that jamming of Radio Free <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> was discontinued Friday and that all other jammers were gradually switched off. The government also stopped jamming <PERSON> Deutsch </PERSON> <PERSON> Welle </PERSON>, a West German station broadcasting in many languages, including Czech, according to a source who spoke to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on condition of anonymity. The Czechoslovak plan to stop obstructing Western broadcasts was announced earlier this week by <PERSON> Pavel </PERSON> and by diplomats in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> attending the Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> executive vice president, said <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> has been jamming the network since 1968. <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON> said that with the Czech move, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> is the last Soviet bloc country that continues to obstruct Radio Free Europe broadcast signals.
