<HEAD>Passengers Lock Man in Jetliner's Bathroom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRISVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man aboard an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet tried to enter the cockpit and then locked himself in a bathroom while other passengers held the door shut, officials said Saturday. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727, carrying 113 passengers from <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, was diverted Friday night to <LOCATION> Raleigh-Durham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, where police arrested <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Saint-Leger </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Damiano </PERSON>, airport public affairs manager. <PERSON> Saint-Leger </PERSON>, 54, of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, was charged with assault on an airport police officer and was held in the <LOCATION> Wake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> jail, Ms. <PERSON> Damiano </PERSON> said. No federal charges have been filed yet. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> interrogated Saint-Leger and other passengers before allowing the flight to continue to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Damiano </PERSON> said. `` The passenger was not armed or dangerous in any way according to the police report,'' Ms. <PERSON> Damiano </PERSON> said. `` He just appeared to be disturbed.''
