<HEAD>Reagan To Focus On Budget After Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> pledged today to work on reforming the nation's budget process after leaving office, calling the effort a `` vital campaign.'' `` The budget system simply has no control and no internal discipline. And that's the problem,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in his weekly radio address, delivered from the Oval Office. With less than five weeks left in his presidency, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> used his five-minute address to argue once again that the president needs greater authority to limit spending in order to curtail the country's deficit. In the 1988 fiscal year, which ended Sept. 30, a $ 155.1 billion deficit was recorded. Under the Gramm-Rudman budget balancing law, a $ 100 billion deficit target has been set for the 1990 fiscal year. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> blamed <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for getting the nation into its red ink dilemma, saying, `` Every dime of deficit spending has been mandated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' Emphasizing that he believes the deficit can be solved without raising taxes, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also said such spending woes could be avoided if a laundry list of changes in the budget process were enacted. The president has argued repeatedly during his White House tenure for the proposals, such as the presidential authority to veto individual items in appropriations bills, a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget, and granting the president authority not to spend money that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has appropriated, among others. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must reform its faulty budget process and we need a balanced budget amendment to the Constitution so that the federal government does not spend more than it takes in,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` After I leave office next month, I will campaign for these reforms. So today, I'm asking you to join me in this vital campaign for the future by making your voice heard. If we achieve these reforms, the deficit will be ancient history in no time,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is required under the law to submit another budget on Jan. 9, and it is expected that he will include his budget reform recommendations in that spending plan. President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has the option of scrapping <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s entire budget if he wants and submitting his won proposal after he takes office Jan. 20 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has declined to say whether he will submit his own plan, but has said he wants to open negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> over ways to reduce the deficit.
