<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Budget 520   12-17 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Budget, 520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Repeats Call For Reforming Federal Budget Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> contended Saturday that the nation's deficit could be `` ancient history in no time'' if the president had more power over the budget process. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who leaves office in less than five weeks, used his weekly radio address to blame <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> once again for the nation's deficit spending habits `` Every dime of deficit spending has been mandated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in the address, delivered from the Oval Office. `` Under the Constitution, only <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can spend money; the president ca n't appropriate a penney,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. In the 1988 fiscal year, which ended Sept. 30, the nation recorded a $ 155.1 billion deficit. Under the Gramm-Rudman budget balancing law, a $ 100 billion deficit target has been set for the 1990 fiscal year. `` The verdict is in. The current system does not work,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did not mention his successor, President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, but he did argue that the nation's red ink woes can be solved without raising taxes, a pledge <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made in his campaign. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is required under the law to submit another budget on Jan. 9, and it is expected that he will include many of his budget reform recommendations in that spending plan. Saying, `` The only way to reduce the deficit is by limiting the increases in spending,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said his final budget will reduce the deficit target by some $ 35 billion for the 1990 fiscal year and meet the Gramm-Rudman target. The president also contended that his budget plan will do so `` without touching Social Security or raising taxes.'' `` Economic growth will increase revenues by $ 80 billion without new taxes. Just by holding spending increases to less than $ 80 billion, we will reduce the deficit and put ourselves on track for a balanced budget by 1993,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has the option of scrapping <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s entire budget if he wants and submitting his won proposal after he takes office Jan. 20. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has declined to say whether he will submit his own plan, but has said he wants to open negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> over ways to reduce the deficit. As he has many times in during his two terms, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> used his five-minute address to argue for an array of changes in the budget process. Many of them grant more power to the president rather to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and have therefore met stiff opposition on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. They include presidential authority to veto individual items in appropriations bills, a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget, and granting the president authority not to spend money that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has appropriated, among others. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must reform its faulty budget process and we need a balanced budget amendment to the Constitution so that the federal government does not spend more than it takes in,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` After I leave office next month, I will campaign for these reforms. So today, I'm asking you to join me in this vital campaign for the future by making your voice heard. If we achieve these reforms, the deficit will be ancient history in no time,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said.
