<HEAD>Papandreou Says He'll Resign if Parliament Rejects Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>, whose socialist administration has been rocked by a financial scandal, said Saturday the government will resign if Parliament does not approve his 1989 budget. The 69-year-old premier told a nationwide television audience that he would consider a rejection of the nearly $ 28 billion budget a no-confidence vote in his socialist government. `` If not approved, the government will resign with all the consequences that would follow such an action'', he said. If the government resigns because of failure to win a majority in the vote scheduled for Sunday, general elections must be held within 45 days. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s speech came as rumors circulated through the Greek capital that the government was about to collapse because of a widening financial scandal. The scandal broke in October when opposition parties charged senior government officials of involvement in illegal deals allegedly set up by banker <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Koskotas </PERSON>, who is accused of influence peddling, embezzlement and fraud. The deals allegedly involved _ directly or indirectly _ the prime minister and members of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Panhellenic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, including <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> George </PERSON>, who is Minister of Education. Seven ministers have left the 59-member Cabinet as a result of the $ 300 million banking and arms scandal. <PERSON> Koskotas </PERSON>, the former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crete </ORGANIZATION>, fled <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> Nov. 6 and has been arrested in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Koskotas </PERSON>, who ran a house-painting business in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from 1974 to 1979, is also charged with attempting to defraud the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. A hearing is scheduled in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> on Jan. 9. On Wednesday, Deputy Defense Minister <PERSON> Stathis </PERSON> <PERSON> Yiotas </PERSON> resigned, saying: `` I refuse as a member of this government to be associated with adventurers, swindlers and embezzlers of public money.'' Yiotas charged the directors of the Greek Arms Industry of paying commissions of millions of dollars for unfulfilled contracts to arms dealers hiding behind dummy companies. He also resigned his seat in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and left the governing party's central committee. The scandal widened when a banking commissioner investigating the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crete </ORGANIZATION> said public service organizations had more than $ 133 million on deposit with the bank. Greek newspapers and opposition political parties accused officials working for the post office, telephone company and other public services of receiving interest rates above the legal limit from the bank and pocketing the difference. In his speech, <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> charged `` domestic and foreign circles'' of `` undermining and orchestrating'' the overthrow of his socialist administration, basing `` their hopes in God that I would not return from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>.'' He did not elaborate. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> underwent bypass cardiac surgery there on September 30. Political observers said <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s speech appeared to be a warning to his deputies to adhere to the party line or _ if they failed to approve the government's budget _ be considered defectors. According to parlia