he point to <PERSON> Pelletreau </PERSON> that `` not everybody is under <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> control'' and can be deterred from terrorism. `` That obviously is not going to be a sustainable position should there be a rash of incidents which we would term terrorism,'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> on Wednesday renounced terrorism `` in all forms.'' The statement was one of three conditions set by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for opening talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. The two other conditions were explicit acceptance of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist and approval of 1967 and 1973 resolutions of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> affirming all Middle Eastern countries should be able to live in peace within secure boundaries A little more than two weeks earlier, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> had condemned the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> as a terrorist organization, called <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> an `` accessory'' to terrorism and denied the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman permission to speak before the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> shifted its debate on the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> dispute to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s decision authorizing `` substantive dialogue'' with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> had not changed <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s view of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> or his opposition to establishment of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state. In fact, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, `` nothing that happened Wednesday has changed our position or approach to the peace process.'' These include the view that an independent Palestinian state on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, which are now held by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, would not be viable, and that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> should not have a separate seat in any <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace talks. `` We have n't pulled back from any of the <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> initiative,'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. He referred to the plan for <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> negotiations <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> took to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> earlier this year. It was not accepted by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, while Palestinian Arabs invited to meet with him in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> did not show up. Key features of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal included a joint delegation of Jordanians and Palestinians to negotiate with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and having <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> give up some _ but not all _ of the land it won in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said <PERSON> Pelletreau </PERSON>'s meeting with <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> officials `` did n't answer any of the tough problems'' but with a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dialogue established it will be easier for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> to understand each other's positions In the past, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> had informed the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> of where the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> stood. `` Cutting o