<HEAD>City Cuts Off Funds For Gang-Control Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> has cut off funds to a gang-control organization once considered a model program for reducing street tension, forcing a halt to its programs. <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> said Friday that the <ORGANIZATION> Crisis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intervention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>'s financial problems, including a $ 203,000 debt to the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, were insurmountable `` We will not use city funds to pay off an old debt,'' he said. The mayor said he hoped the private, non-profit agency's program and employees could be absorbed by another agency so that its work could continue, but he said no alternatives have been explored. The group's executive director, <PERSON> Bennie </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Swans </PERSON>, said 38 of the 48 employees were laid off Friday and its programs were shut down. He said he and the other nine employees would stay until Jan. 5, when city funding ends, to tie up loose ends and try to find another source of funds. `` Everyone agrees we've performed a valuable service,'' Swans said. `` I think that the services are sorely needed in the community and I think people are going to suffer because of it.'' The decision to close the agency came after months of uncertainty over its future, sparked by complaints of financial mismanagement. The Crisis Intervention Network was founded in 1975 as an arm of city government. Its approach to gang warfare _ using street-savvy workers, many of them former gang members, to mediate disputes and reduce community tension _ won praise and became a model for programs around the country. The network became a private, non-profit agency in 1979, but the city has remained its principal source of funds, with city contracts paying $ 1.5 million or more in each of the past three years. But three months ago, a group of current and former employees wrote to elected officials and news media accusing Swans of spending abuses and mismanagement. Swans called the allegations groundless, but acknowledged bookkeeping problems, including a failure to send to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> about $ 80,000 withheld from employee paychecks. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> filed a $ 203,000 lien against the network Dec. 9, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON>, co-chairman of the agency's board. He said the board had not decided `` whether it's over, whether to reorganize, bankruptcy. ... We have choices.'' `` I think the city has gotten used to CIN stepping in when things get hot,'' <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON> said. `` We are the envy of cities around the country. It just seems unnecessary and detrimental for the city to cut off the funding.''
