who can not be named in line with standing regulations. The house in <LOCATION> Sultaniyeh </LOCATION> was one mile southwest of <LOCATION> Tibnin </LOCATION>, where the Irishmen were abducted. The 620-strong Irish batallion serving with <ORGANIZATION> UNIFIL </ORGANIZATION> is headquartered in <LOCATION> Tibnin </LOCATION>, a village 13 miles north of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> which borders <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s six-to-10-mile self-proclaimed security zone. The police spokesman identified the three rescued Irish soldiers as <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeken </PERSON>, 35, Pvt <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearney </PERSON>, 25, and Pvt. <PERSON> Bernak </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarugmey </PERSON>, 30. <ORGANIZATION> UNIFIL </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Timur </PERSON> <PERSON> Goksel </PERSON> said <PERSON> Amal </PERSON> returned the three to their command. `` They are in good shape,'' <PERSON> Goksel </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. The abductions apparently were intended to retaliate for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s seizure Thursday of Faithful Resistance guerrilla commander <PERSON> Jawad </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasfi </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Tibnin </LOCATION> The Israeli military command said <PERSON> Kasfi </PERSON> was linked to attacks on Israeli army forces and an Israeli-backed militia, the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, since 1984. <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> worker <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Winkler </PERSON>, 32, was freed Friday night in the southern city of <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>, where he was abducted Nov. 17. Police said <PERSON> Winkler </PERSON> boarded a ferry Saturday at the Christian port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION>, heading for <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. The Swiss Foreign Ministry earlier said <PERSON> Winkler </PERSON> was to