<HEAD>Rostropovich Joins Charity Concert for Quake Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with concert taking place; no pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet-born cellist <PERSON> Mstislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON> played in a charity concert for Armenian earthquake victims Saturday night after postponing a visit to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to take part in the event. `` It was very important for me to take part in this concert,'' the 61-year-old musician said before a last-minute rehearsal with flutist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Galway </PERSON>, conductor <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Previn </PERSON> and other musicians who rearranged their schedules and donated time to perform. Prince <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, heir to the British throne, and his wife, Princess <PERSON> Diana </PERSON>, attended the sell-out concert at the 2,026-seat Barbican Hall in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The event was part of an effort called `` Musicians for <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>,'' which was expected to raise $ 452,000 from donations worldwide, including gifts from musicians, concert proceeds and film and recording rights. The British <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Concert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION> organized the appeal to aid some of the thousands of survivors from the killer earthquake Dec. 7 that killed an estimated 55,000 people. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and five other nations televised the late-night performance. The <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s world service rearranged its radio programming to allow its estimated audience of 25 million to hear the concert live. `` At the moment, with what has happened, I feel that all Armenians are my relatives,'' said <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen of Armenian descent who is conductor of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. On Friday, <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON>, one of the most famous cellists in history, gave his first solo concert in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in nearly two decades, also in aid of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Previn </PERSON>, who conducted the English Chamber Orchestra during the concert Saturday, said before the program that it was `` amazing'' the musicians were able to join. `` In our business everyone's booked up for the next two or three years,'' he said. `` It was just good fortune that everyone could make it at such short notice.'' `` This terrible catastrophe has provoked the best qualities in people,'' said <PERSON> Rostropovich </PERSON>. The cellist played <PERSON> Villa-Lobos </PERSON>' Bachianas Brasileiras No. 1, then turned to the piano to accompany his Soviet-born wife, soprano <PERSON> Galina </PERSON> <PERSON> Vishnevskaya </PERSON>, in works by <PERSON> Tchaikovsky </PERSON>. The program also included <LOCATION> Galway </LOCATION> playing <PERSON> Debussy </PERSON>'s Syrinx and <PERSON> Previn </PERSON> conducting the English Chamber Orchestra in <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s Coriolan Overture Soviet pianist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Gavrilov </PERSON>, whose family in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> escaped injury in the quake, played <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chopin </PERSON>. The musicians also included violist <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Bashmet </PERSON>, pianist <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> and violinist <PERSON> Cho-Liang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lin </PERSON>. The Times reported that the concert was to be televised in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Musicians, organizers, concert hall workers, program printers and other staff