<HEAD>Soviet Military Plane To Fly Volunteers To Armenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE RULE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A crew planning to take durable, plastic tents to earthquake victims in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> got word Saturday that a Soviet military cargo plane will carry them to the disaster site, the group's leader said. The 17-member team is scheduled to leave Sunday, said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Seraphin </PERSON>, president of Protect-A-Boat and Film Applicators of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, company that came up with the idea for the quick-to-build shelters. `` As far as we know, we're ready to go,'' he said, but added that he'll `` believe it when we're on the plane.'' There was no immediate word on when the plane would return to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> with materials it has picked up in other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities. Soviet officials estimate 55,000 lives were lost and 500,000 people were left homeless by the Dec. 7 quake. After hearing of the massive displacement, <PERSON> Seraphin </PERSON> came up with the idea of using the film for tents. Construction techniques require building frames out of steel and then shrink-wrapping them with resin-based plastic using a propane heat gun. <PERSON> Seraphin </PERSON> said a tent that can house 30 people takes about two hours to build and includes doors, windows and vents. The arrival of the Soviet plane would end two days of frustration for <PERSON> Seraphin </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-based <ORGANIZATION> Armenia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` In the past two days, I would ` guesstimate' that we've contacted close to 100 people from the secretary of state on down to business people with contacts,'' <PERSON> Seraphin </PERSON> said, adding he had talked to people in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATIO