<HEAD>Energy Secretary Warns of Further Weapons Plant Shutdowns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Energy Department may have to shut more nuclear weapons facilities because President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is not proposing enough money to operate them in accordance with safety and environmental laws, the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said in its Sunday editions. The newspaper cited a letter in which <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> warned the administration that the proposed 1990 budget fell short by $ 360 million. `` I must in good conscience advise you that ... the system will, in all likelihood, be operating beyond the bounds of acceptable risk,'' <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> said in the Dec. 9 letter to White House chief of staff <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duberstein </PERSON>. Spokespersons for the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the White House were not available for comment after the story appeared. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, the letter contains a detailed assessment of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s budgetary problems, which <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> said may require choosing between upgrading plant safety and meeting the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s production goals for nuclear materials. If the department gives priority to production goals, the paper quoted <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON>, `` then unresolved environmental and safety issues are likely to lead to further shutdowns in the weapons complex.'' <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON>'s letter cites years of budget austerity combined with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> military buildup that put more demands on the system. `` Part of today's problem stems from our attempts to stretch, defer and absorb budgetary shortfalls, hoping that next year things would be better and we could catch up,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON>. `` As a result, the country's ability to produce and maintain a nuclear weapons stockpile is in serious jeopardy,'' <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> said in the letter. `` The risk is great that without a significant increase in resources over the next five years, we will no longer be able to sustain a strong nuclear deterrent in which we have invested $ 57 billion since 1980.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which operates 17 weapons plants, has proposed spending $ 50 billion in the next 20 years to build new facilities and correct the most pressing environmental problems. <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> told <PERSON> Duberstein </PERSON> his department would pay for $ 200 million in upgrades at its <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plants, in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, by using the last of a contingency fund. He said the action will reduce the fund `` to zero'' and leave no cushion for emergencies. In addition, the department has said it will help clear up a nuclear waste problem endangering the operation of the Denver-area <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION>, which handles plutonium. <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON>'s letter, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, indicated the department is in line for a $ 900 million budget increase next year _ more than 8 percent higher than its current $ 12 billion budget. The secretary said the problems at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and Rocky Flats will result in a $ 360 million shortfall, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>.
