<TEXT>
 The Energy Department should be able to meet conditions set by three governors for resolving a deadlock over the storage of radioactive waste from nuclear weapons plants, a department official said. The governors of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> emerged from a private meeting Friday with pledges of cooperation from Deputy Energy Secretary <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON>. `` I think we've laid a solid groundwork for progress. We've put a process in place. ... I believe it will bear fruit,'' <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON> said. But the governors said they would continue to pressure the government to make sure the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> honors its promise to hasten the opening of the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a prototype storage facility under construction near <LOCATION> Carlsbad </LOCATION>, N.M.
